aesop_section_1_5.response: Gratitude and kindness are never forgotten.

aesop_section_1_58.moral: Men often applaud an imitation and hiss the real thing.

aesop_section_1_75.response: What is valuable to one may be worthless to another.

aesop_section_1_80.response: Little by little does the trick.
aesop_section_1_80.moral: Little by little does the trick.

aesop_section_1_101.moral: How often do we supply our enemies with the means of our own destruction.

aesop_section_2_5.response: Threats are empty until backed by action.

aesop_section_2_7.response: Kindness to the ungrateful will bring harm to the giver.

aesop_section_2_8.response: You are judged by the company you keep.

aesop_section_2_16.response: Do not rely on charm when hard work is needed.

aesop_section_2_25.response: United we stand, divided we fall.

perry_18.response: Expect no help from those who are naturally harmful.

aesop_section_2_28.response: Better one safe way than a hundred on which you cannot reckon.

aesop_section_2_29.response: Cunning often recoils on the schemer.

aesop_section_2_30.moral: Do unto others what you would have them do unto you.

perry_123.response: Do not let flattery cloud your judgment.
perry_123.moral: Flatters are not to be trusted.

aesop_section_2_32.response: Beware of flatterers who seek to deceive you.

aesop_section_2_38.response: It is better to endure a lesser evil than to risk a greater one.

aesop_section_2_48.moral: There is as much malice in a wink as in a word.

aesop_section_2_52.response: Be careful what you wish for, as it may bring more harm than good.

aesop_section_2_73.response: Pride can lead to one's downfall.

aesop_section_2_74.response: No one can escape their fate by hiding.

aesop_section_2_77.response: Those who mock others may find themselves in a worse fate.

aesop_section_2_80.response: Strife grows greater with conflict, but diminishes with peace.

aesop_section_2_91.response: Do not seek what you are not prepared to face.

aesop_section_2_92.response: Too much of a good thing can lead to dissatisfaction.

aesop_section_3_3.response: Attempting to imitate others can lead to losing one's own unique talents.

aesop_section_3_4.response: Do not trust the promises of those who have nothing to lose.

aesop_section_3_8.response: Necessity is the mother of invention.

aesop_section_3_13.response: Those who can easily escape their commitments are not to be trusted.

aesop_section_3_24.response: Learn from the misfortunes of others.

aesop_section_3_32.response: Honesty is the best policy, even in embarrassing situations.

aesop_section_3_37.response: Avoid those who are inconsistent in their actions.

aesop_section_3_39.response: The story is told by the victor.

aesop_section_3_45.response: The trappings of leadership can become a hindrance in times of danger.

aesop_section_3_50.response: Do not count your chickens before they are hatched.

aesop_section_3_52.response: If you try to please all, you please none.

aesop_section_3_62.moral: Don't make a big fuss over nothing.

aesop_section_3_65.response: Do not trust everything you hear.

aesop_section_3_66.response: Do not boast of abilities you do not possess.

aesop_section_3_70.response: Yielding to challenges can lead to survival.

aesop_section_3_81.response: Misplaced confidence can lead to unexpected danger.
aesop_section_3_81.moral: Trouble comes from the direction we least expect it.

aesop_section_3_89.moral: Be content with your lot; one cannot be first in everything.

aesop_section_3_91.response: Consider the hidden value in things before discarding them.

aesop_section_3_97.moral: Those who would mend others, should first mend themselves.

aesop_section_3_98.response: Change of habit cannot alter nature.
aesop_section_3_98.moral: Change of habit cannot alter nature.

aesop_section_4_10.response: It is useless to attack the unyielding.

aesop_section_4_18.moral: A liar deceives no one but himself.

aesop_section_4_23.response: Quality is more valuable than speed.

gibbs_170_44.moral: Self-preservation can sometimes take precedence over kinship

gibbs_171_45.moral: Someone who lays a trap for others will fall victim to it himself.

gibbs_172_137.response: Those who show no mercy will find none.
gibbs_172_137.moral: People who lay traps for others should be careful not to fall into a trap themselves.

gibbs_173_426.response: Do not let fleeting pleasures lead to your downfall.
gibbs_173_426.moral: Men feel worst when they contribute to their own undoing.

gibbs_176_87.response: Beware of trusting those with hidden motives.
gibbs_176_87.moral: Households and cities are most likely to be deserted when there are harsh people in charge.

gibbs_178_95.response: Beware of false friends and their deceitful intentions.
gibbs_178_95.moral: Rushing into pleasant invitations can lead to dire consequences.

gibbs_179_380.response: We easily ignore what does not concern us.
gibbs_179_380.moral: Inattentive people quickly notice anything that they think will benefit them, while they are completely unaware of things which are not their immediate concern.

gibbs_180_424.response: Do not mock the misfortunes of others, for they may reveal your own shortcomings.
gibbs_180_424.moral: Do not laugh at the calamity that befalls your neighbour.

gibbs_181_37.response: Instinct can reveal the truth even when the senses cannot.
gibbs_181_37.moral: Evil tendencies are shown in early life.

gibbs_183_388.response: Respect the contributions of others, even as their abilities wane.
gibbs_183_388.moral: Rewards do not always accompany a lifetime of good work.

gibbs_184_422.response: It is hard to bear the insults of the weak when one has fallen from power.

gibbs_185_449.response: It is wise to prepare for trouble before it arises.
gibbs_185_449.moral: Preparedness for war is the best guarantee of peace.

gibbs_186_61.response: Those who unite against a common threat can avoid mutual destruction.
gibbs_186_61.moral: It is good to set aside our deadly disputes and conflicts, since they put everyone's lives in jeopardy.

gibbs_187_376.response: Those who live by violence will eventually fall by it.
gibbs_187_376.moral: What you have done to others will likewise be done to you, according to the same measure.

gibbs_189_289.response: Criticism is best given after the crisis is resolved.

gibbs_190_291.response: Some people complain about others when they themselves are at fault.
gibbs_190_291.moral: Anything which is done at the wrong time is liable to be ridiculed.

gibbs_191_540.response: Deceit and dishonesty will not go unnoticed.
gibbs_191_540.moral: An honest man's word is as good as his oath.

gibbs_192_200.response: Pride often leads to downfall, while humility offers protection.
gibbs_192_200.moral: Better poverty without care, than riches with.

gibbs_194_495.response: True beauty lies in one's character, not in outward appearance.
gibbs_194_495.moral: Inner beauty is better than outer beauty.

gibbs_195_224.response: Some people overestimate their own importance.
gibbs_195_224.moral: Some men are of more consequence in their own eyes than in the eyes of their neighbors.

gibbs_196_477.response: Do not make promises you cannot keep.
gibbs_196_477.moral: Dishonesty can lead to dire consequences.

gibbs_198_242.response: Do not give importance to those who seek to elevate themselves through your attention.
gibbs_198_242.moral: People who enter into contests with unworthy opponents lower their own reputation.

gibbs_199_233.response: When facing a greater threat, lesser annoyances lose their power.
gibbs_199_233.moral: When you are besieged by powerful people, you are subject to vicious attacks by anyone and everyone.

gibbs_200_55.response: Choose allies who are able to assist you.
gibbs_200_55.moral: When we form friendships with one another, we must choose allies who can come to our aid in moments of peril.

gibbs_201_59.response: United we stand, divided we fall.
gibbs_201_59.moral: Unity is strength, while division invites defeat.

gibbs_203_106.response: Beware of those who offer false praise with hidden motives.
gibbs_203_106.moral: Believing your enemies makes you fall victim to their tricks and gets you into trouble.

gibbs_204_165.response: Modesty and respect earn more than greed and presumption.
gibbs_204_165.moral: Those who take by force are met with resistance, while those who approach with humility may find unexpected generosity.

gibbs_208_566.response: It is better to endure criticism from afar than to suffer harm up close.
gibbs_208_566.moral: It is best to keep negative influences away.

gibbs_213_598.response: Those who learn from their mistakes grow wiser.
gibbs_213_598.moral: Experience teaches valuable lessons and encourages caution.

gibbs_215_354.response: Do not try to imitate others if it is not in your nature.
gibbs_215_354.moral: Jealousy can lead people to foolishly imitate their betters.

gibbs_216_268.moral: Familiarity mollifies even the most terrifying things.

gibbs_217_510.response: Greed can lead to losing what you already have.
gibbs_217_510.moral: People who grasp for more than they need are deprived of what they have.

gibbs_219_98.response: Beware of those who come with ill intentions disguised as friendship.
gibbs_219_98.moral: Beware of when the powerful and the deceitful collaborate.

gibbs_220_118.response: Promises made in desperation are often forgotten.
gibbs_220_118.moral: Be cautious with promises made under duress.

gibbs_223_129.response: When someone is determined to act unjustly, they will find any excuse to do so.

gibbs_224_105.response: Flattery and insults are powerless against those who remain steadfast.

gibbs_226_128.response: Beware of those who sow discord for their own gain.
gibbs_226_128.moral: Gossips are to be seen and not heard.

gibbs_227_435.response: Sometimes the solution can be worse than the problem.
gibbs_227_435.moral: Relying too much on subordinates can lead to unintended consequences.

gibbs_230_156.response: Treat others as you would like to be treated.

gibbs_231_187.moral: When the evidence is fairly weighed, a colourfully painted lie is quickly refuted by the facts.

gibbs_233_305.response: Do not waste your efforts on the invulnerable.
gibbs_233_305.moral: It is useless attacking the insensible.

gibbs_234_542.response: People with conflicting interests cannot live together in harmony.

gibbs_235_83.response: Gratitude should be shown to those who have helped you, but wisdom lies in securing your future.
gibbs_235_83.moral: Favor those who do you kindness.

gibbs_236_107.response: Beware of flattery and deceitful intentions.
gibbs_236_107.moral: A discerning person is made wise by the misfortunes of his neighbours.

gibbs_237_272.response: Do not underestimate the value of small things.
gibbs_237_272.moral: Do not go chasing after things that are useless and unprofitable.

gibbs_238_73.moral: Those who do you a favour you must repay kind.

gibbs_239_16.response: Flattery will not protect you from the deceitful.
gibbs_239_16.moral: The penalty for speaking and for keeping silent is one and the same.

gibbs_241_408.response: Better a simple life in peace than a rich life in fear.
gibbs_241_408.moral: It is better to live in self-sufficient poverty than to be tormented by the worries of wealth.

gibbs_242_592.response: People often prefer illusion over reality.
gibbs_242_592.moral: Men will stand behind a judgment made in error until the actual fact of the matter later compels them to regret their choice.

gibbs_243_519.moral: It is natural to be a knave; men must rise above.

gibbs_244_588.response: Deception may bring temporary success, but truth will ultimately prevail.
gibbs_244_588.moral: Beware of swindlers, as they often exploit the gullibility of others.

gibbs_246_599.response: Foolishness leads to one's own downfall.
gibbs_246_599.moral: Avoid mischief and taking excessive risks.

gibbs_247_14.response: Might makes right for those who wield power unjustly.
gibbs_247_14.moral: An alliance made with the high and mighty can never be trusted.

gibbs_249_547.response: Greed and fear can paralyze decision-making.
gibbs_249_547.moral: Wealth is of little value if one is too afraid to use or enjoy it.

gibbs_250_251.response: Threats are empty to those who refuse to be intimidated.
gibbs_250_251.moral: True courage involves overcoming fears, even when faced with intimidation.

gibbs_251_333.response: Be content with your natural place and abilities.
gibbs_251_333.moral: Contentment with our lot is an element of happiness.

gibbs_254_296.response: Beware of those who speak with deceitful intentions.
gibbs_254_296.moral: Don't be seduced by deceptive words, they will cause nothing but trouble.

gibbs_256_193.response: Fine feathers don't make fine birds.
gibbs_256_193.moral: The useful is of much more importance and value, than the ornamental.

gibbs_258_302.response: Be cautious and discerning in your actions, for appearances can be deceiving.
gibbs_258_302.moral: You should not treat bad people the same way that you treat good people.

gibbs_259_340.response: Do not blindly imitate others without understanding their circumstances.
gibbs_259_340.moral: You must not act unnaturally, trying to achieve some impossible thing.

gibbs_260_102.response: Beware of false assurances from those with hidden motives.
gibbs_260_102.moral: If you try to deceive someone who has his wits about him, you will waste your time and be made fun of as well.

gibbs_262_168.response: In trying to escape one danger, we may fall into another.
gibbs_262_168.moral: Those who commit grave wrongs cannot escape justice.

gibbs_264_89.response: Do not give away what you cannot afford to lose.

gibbs_265_326.response: Pride and pretension lead to downfall.
gibbs_265_326.moral: Live your lives in the clothes that suit you.

gibbs_266_475.response: The truth will reveal itself, even to those who try to hide it.
gibbs_266_475.moral: Thieves may find themselves entangled in their own deceit.

gibbs_267_507.response: Do not envy the gifts of others, for each has their own unique talents.
gibbs_267_507.moral: Be content with your lot; one cannot be first in everything.

gibbs_268_328.moral: Do not boast to have something you do not.

gibbs_269_194.response: Do not boast of burdens that bind you.
gibbs_269_194.moral: Many children are a great blessing; but a few good ones are a greater.

gibbs_272_319.response: Envy will not grant you the talents of others.
gibbs_272_319.moral: Those who assume a character which does not belong to them, only make themselves ridiculous.

gibbs_273_111.response: Cunning and collaboration can overcome even the strongest defenses.
gibbs_273_111.moral: Beware of when the powerful and the deceitful collaborate.

gibbs_274_112.response: Beware of those who offer help with selfish intentions.

gibbs_275_465.response: Pride and despair can lead to ruin, but fortune may favor those who endure.
gibbs_275_465.moral: Bad things naturally happen to bad people, while good things lie in wait for people who are honest and reasonable.

gibbs_279_548.response: You cannot please everyone at the same time.

gibbs_282_484.response: Be careful what you wish for, as you may not truly desire it.
gibbs_282_484.moral: Be careful what you wish for.

gibbs_284_286.response: Greed can lead to losing what you already have.
gibbs_284_286.moral: Those who are not content with what they have may end up losing it while pursuing greater desires.

gibbs_286_90.response: Kindness without discernment can lead to one's own ruin.
gibbs_286_90.moral: Good will is worth nothing unless it is accompanied by good acts.

gibbs_287_459.response: In seeking to escape one danger, do not rush into another.
gibbs_287_459.moral: In avoiding a lesser danger, one may inadvertently fall into a greater peril.

gibbs_288_80.response: Do not harm those who help you.

gibbs_289_457.response: Beware of dangers from unexpected directions.

gibbs_291_559.response: Do not believe everything you hear, for some tales are too good to be true.
gibbs_291_559.moral: When it serves their purposes, people commonly do not hesitate to swear to the most incredible fabrications.

gibbs_293_85.moral: Someone who assists both the truly good and those who are undeserving is not seen as a philanthropist, but is instead regarded as a madman.

gibbs_296_585.response: Too much optimism can blind one to reality.
gibbs_296_585.moral: A death-bed flattery is the worst of treacheries.

gibbs_298_589.moral: Few things are done except for profit.

gibbs_299_586.response: Timely advice is the most valuable.
gibbs_299_586.moral: Do not play the wise man after the fact.

gibbs_300_400.response: What is valuable to one may be worthless to another.
gibbs_300_400.moral: Different people are interested in different things.

gibbs_301_228.response: Do not pursue what you cannot handle.
gibbs_301_228.moral: It is a foolish man who wants to rival his superiors.

gibbs_302_373.moral: Do not believe those who have ill intentions.

gibbs_303_442.response: Do not attempt the impossible at the cost of your own well-being.
gibbs_303_442.moral: Do not try to do impossible things.

gibbs_304_381.response: False sympathy is often a mask for self-interest.
gibbs_304_381.moral: False sympathy often masks selfish intentions.

gibbs_305_338.response: Do not try to be something you are not.
gibbs_305_338.moral: Do not try to gain favor by acting in a way that is contrary to your own nature and character.

gibbs_307_292.response: When desperation sets in, even the most loyal may be sacrificed.
gibbs_307_292.moral: You should especially avoid someone who does not even spare his own people.

gibbs_309_30.response: Beware of false friends who offer freedom at the cost of loyalty.
gibbs_309_30.moral: Trust is not to be given lightly.

gibbs_310_116.response: Give an inch, and they'll take a mile.
gibbs_310_116.moral: There is danger lurking in the words of a wicked person.

gibbs_311_263.response: Do not grasp at more than you need.
gibbs_311_263.moral: Do not grasp at more than you need.

gibbs_312_149.response: Cunning and wisdom can outsmart deceit.
gibbs_312_149.moral: Those who try to deceive may expect to be paid in their own coin.

gibbs_313_498.response: True kindness and care are more valuable than mere biological ties.
gibbs_313_498.moral: Men are averse to fixed rules, but are won by kind services.

gibbs_314_174.response: Falsehood and injustice will eventually meet their own punishment.
gibbs_314_174.moral: Wicked liars generally get their just consequences.

gibbs_315_175.response: False testimony can lead to unjust outcomes.
gibbs_315_175.moral: Often justice is the captive of criminal deceit.

gibbs_316_430.response: Do not assume all things are as they appear.
gibbs_316_430.moral: They who act without sufficient thought, will often fall into unsuspected danger

gibbs_317_196.response: Quality is more important than speed.
gibbs_317_196.moral: Enterprise is not to be judged in terms of its speed but its outcome.

gibbs_318_405.response: Greed can lead to one's downfall.

gibbs_319_117.response: Never trust the promises of those in dire straits.
gibbs_319_117.moral: Take what you can get when you can get it.

gibbs_322_232.response: Do not mistake the source of your strength.
gibbs_322_232.moral: Do not take pride in the good qualities that actually belong to someone else.

gibbs_324_77.moral: Benefits are refused by those who don't understand them.

gibbs_326_374.response: Do not pretend to be a friend while acting as an enemy.
gibbs_326_374.moral: No one can be a friend if you know not whether to trust or distrust him.

gibbs_328_88.response: Beware of those who offer gifts with hidden intentions.
gibbs_328_88.moral: People who offer to give someone many gifts are no doubt trying to deceive.

gibbs_329_68.response: Do not blame others for the consequences of your own actions.
gibbs_329_68.moral: Do not blame others for the circumstances of their upbringing.

gibbs_330_32.response: Do not trust the advice of your enemies.
gibbs_330_32.moral: Do not give up friends for foes.

gibbs_332_160.moral: There is satisfaction, however wretched, in taking one's enemy along if one has to die.

gibbs_333_390.response: People often overlook the harm caused by those they are familiar with.
gibbs_333_390.moral: Some can do wrong more easily than others can see it.

gibbs_335_145.response: Those who betray others for their own gain will find themselves betrayed in turn.

gibbs_336_322.moral: Clothes may disguise a fool, but his words will give him away.

gibbs_338_147.response: Those who plot the downfall of others often meet their own demise.
gibbs_338_147.moral: People who lay traps for others bring about their own destruction.

gibbs_339_410.response: Envy not the privileges of others, for they may come with hidden burdens.

gibbs_340_418.moral: Be cautious of pride, as nobody knows what the future may bring.

gibbs_341_114.moral: People are quick to promise but reluctant to give.

gibbs_343_217.response: Even the most unlikely can be useful with the right guidance.
gibbs_343_217.moral: The loud-mouthed boaster does not impress nor frighten those who know him.

gibbs_344_404.response: Possession without understanding is of little value.
gibbs_344_404.moral: Talent is wasted when it's in the hands of the unappreciative.

gibbs_345_64.response: Do not envy others without understanding their burdens.
gibbs_345_64.moral: Instead of looking at how things start, we should look instead at how they turn out in the end.

gibbs_346_10.response: Be careful what you wish for, as things could always be worse.
gibbs_346_10.moral: People often appreciate what they had only after experiencing something worse.

gibbs_348_5.response: Freedom comes with its own risks and responsibilities.
gibbs_348_5.moral: The insubordinate are free from both obligation and protection.

gibbs_349_11.response: When there is no change in your burden, the identity of your master is irrelevant.
gibbs_349_11.moral: In a change of government, the poor change nothing beyond the name of their master.

gibbs_350_307.response: A person is known by the company they keep.
gibbs_350_307.moral: A man is known by the company he keeps.

gibbs_353_414.response: Avoid what is tainted by misfortune.
gibbs_353_414.moral: Easy life and seeming good fortune of others conceal a threat to their welfare.

gibbs_356_568.response: Do not ask for the impossible.

gibbs_357_235.response: Do not let pride lead you into danger.
gibbs_357_235.moral: False confidence often leads into danger.

gibbs_359_486.response: Stubbornness leads to one's own downfall.
gibbs_359_486.moral: You can't always stop a fool.

gibbs_361_325.response: Pretending to be someone you are not can leave you with nothing.
gibbs_361_325.moral: Greed for more can lead to losing what you already have.

gibbs_363_406.response: A life without purpose or reward is a life unfulfilled.
gibbs_363_406.moral: A life of greed and hoarding wealth leads to misery.

gibbs_364_279.response: Do not let your imagination inflate your expectations.
gibbs_364_279.moral: Our mere anticipations of life outrun its realities.

gibbs_367_558.response: Some habits are harder to break than they seem.
gibbs_367_558.moral: It's hard to give up bad habits.

gibbs_368_22.response: Beauty without strength is insufficient for leadership.
gibbs_368_22.moral: Beauty alone does not qualify one for leadership.

gibbs_369_51.response: Do not seek alliances with those who cannot help you.
gibbs_369_51.moral: Count the cost before you commit yourselves.

gibbs_371_155.response: The treacherous are often caught in their own trap.

gibbs_372_142.response: Do not mock the misfortune of others, for fate may soon catch up with you.
gibbs_372_142.moral: It is a foolish thing to give advice to others while not looking out for oneself.

gibbs_375_57.response: Do not be deceived by empty promises.
gibbs_375_57.moral: Some people will do anything to get what they want.

gibbs_378_348.response: Be content with who you are.
gibbs_378_348.moral: He who competes with his superiors destroys himself before he can equal them.

gibbs_380_159.response: Hatred can blind us to our own peril.
gibbs_380_159.moral: Some people are so consumed by hatred that they would rather suffer themselves than see their enemies succeed.

gibbs_382_357.response: Those who engage in wrongdoing may find themselves trapped by their own actions.
gibbs_382_357.moral: People with a history of wrongdoing are often not trusted.

gibbs_383_416.response: Fortune can change swiftly, and past glory does not guarantee future ease.
gibbs_383_416.moral: Do not boast too much at the height of your powers; people often spend their old age worn out with toil and trouble.

gibbs_385_595.response: Do not mock others for circumstances beyond their control.
gibbs_385_595.moral: The only thing that can really bring shame on a man is a punishment that he has justly deserved.

gibbs_386_285.response: Greed can lead to losing everything.
gibbs_386_285.moral: Do not try to grasp too much at once.

gibbs_387_336.response: No one can escape their fate by hiding from it.
gibbs_387_336.moral: The master has better insight than anyone else when it comes to his own business.

gibbs_388_437.moral: Bad neighbours are the first to suffer from the harm they would do to others.

gibbs_390_438.response: Do not invite danger into your own home.
gibbs_390_438.moral: Do not take on more than you can handle.

gibbs_391_124.response: Depend on those who are reliable and ask for nothing in return.
gibbs_391_124.moral: Charity begins at home, but this does not prevent the further exercise of it.

gibbs_392_379.response: Take responsibility for your own actions.
gibbs_392_379.moral: Those who complain about their duties often forget their own role in creating the situation.

gibbs_394_74.response: Trust, once broken, is not easily mended.
gibbs_394_74.moral: He who harms someone should henceforth be treated with suspicion.

gibbs_395_75.response: Some wounds are too deep to mend.
gibbs_395_75.moral: Injuries may be forgiven, but not forgotten.

gibbs_397_358.response: Prejudices are hard to overcome, even with good deeds.
gibbs_397_358.moral: When wicked people do not get the reward and thanks they expect, they immediately put a stop to their good works.

gibbs_399_494.response: Hard work and diligence bring their own rewards.
gibbs_399_494.moral: Man's greatest treasure consists in work.

gibbs_400_466.response: Excessive caution can lead to the very misfortune one seeks to avoid.
gibbs_400_466.moral: We had better bear our troubles bravely than try to escape them.

gibbs_405_240.response: The small and nimble can often escape danger that ensnares the large and unwary.
gibbs_405_240.moral: To be small is a way to stay safe and avoid problems, whereas you rarely see a man with a big reputation who is able to keep out of danger.

gibbs_410_337.response: Do not attempt what you do not understand.
gibbs_410_337.moral: Imitation is no substitute for knowledge.

gibbs_412_419.response: Do not count your chickens before they hatch.
gibbs_412_419.moral: We have to endure reversals of fortune, since we know that life is a matter of luck.

gibbs_413_420.response: Fortune can come when least expected.
gibbs_413_420.moral: Luck often bestows the things that skill cannot obtain.

gibbs_414_546.response: One person's gain may be another's loss.
gibbs_414_546.moral: Some never understand the actions of others.

gibbs_415_226.response: Gratitude and kindness can bring protection and favor.
gibbs_415_226.moral: A reward for one might be destruction for another.

gibbs_416_120.response: Do not tolerate even the smallest of evils.
gibbs_416_120.moral: No mercy should be shown to someone who is wicked, regardless of whether his wickedness is great or small.

gibbs_417_427.response: Greed can lead to one's downfall.

gibbs_418_223.response: Empty threats are powerless against true authority.
gibbs_418_223.moral: Ignore complainers who have no influence.

gibbs_419_84.response: Help those in need, and they may repay you in the future.
gibbs_419_84.moral: We should do favours for someone who can do us a good deed in return.

gibbs_421_413.response: Wealth can lead to corruption and should be approached with caution.
gibbs_421_413.moral: Coffers of cash put a stop to honest traffic in praise.

gibbs_422_417.response: Accept the changes that life brings.

gibbs_424_550.moral: Outside show is a poor substitute for inner worth.

gibbs_426_237.response: Slow and steady wins the race.
gibbs_426_237.moral: Slow and steady wins the race.

gibbs_429_552.response: Evil companions bring more harm than good.
gibbs_429_552.moral: A wicked person deservedly comes to a bad end by keeping company with other wicked people.

gibbs_430_255.response: It is easy to despise what you cannot have.
gibbs_430_255.moral: It's easy to despise what you cannot have.

gibbs_432_596.response: Beware of those who disguise their deceit as skill.
gibbs_432_596.moral: Overly curious people often pay a very high price for recklessly indulging their curiosity.

gibbs_433_444.moral: People who act impulsively can end up in regrettable situations.

gibbs_434_365.moral: Ambiguity in character can lead to mistrust.

gibbs_437_195.response: Quality is more important than quantity.
gibbs_437_195.moral: Quality is more valuable than quantity.

gibbs_440_222.response: Do not mock others for their misfortunes, for circumstances can change for anyone.

gibbs_441_18.moral: Take warning from the misfortunes of others.

gibbs_443_188.response: Boasting is pointless when the truth cannot be challenged.
gibbs_443_188.moral: Deceivers often exploit the inability of others to challenge their falsehoods.

gibbs_444_264.response: Do not let illusions lead you to ruin.
gibbs_444_264.moral: Greedy men chase after profit with such an intensity that they destroy themselves without achieving anything.

gibbs_445_148.moral: Stay vigilant and think before you speak.

gibbs_447_146.response: Betrayal and treachery will ultimately lead to one's own downfall.
gibbs_447_146.moral: Take pleasure when thieves destroy themselves.

gibbs_448_398.response: Do not trust advice from those who stand to gain from it.
gibbs_448_398.moral: Distrust advice from someone who stands to gain.

gibbs_452_269.moral: Familiarity makes it easy to confront even frightening situations.

gibbs_453_17.response: Flattery and cunning can outwit malice.
gibbs_453_17.moral: Someone who plots against others falls into his own trap.

gibbs_454_593.moral: Beware of those who appear busy but achieve little of value.

gibbs_455_270.response: Do not let fear of the unknown overpower your judgment.

gibbs_456_490.response: It is wise to heed the advice of those who see danger ahead.
gibbs_456_490.moral: People who stubbornly cling to unwise choices lose everything before they know it.
